lessons.theory:
## The error channel is part of the sender's type

Every sender in `std::execution` declares three things:
- which **value types** it can deliver via `set_value`,
- which **error types** it can deliver via `set_error`,
- whether it can complete via `set_stopped` (cancellation).

This means a sender that carries `std::error_code` as its error type is a different type from one that carries `std::exception_ptr`. The type system checks consistency at compile time:

```cpp
// A sender that either returns int or signals std::error_code as an error:
auto s = std::execution::just_error(std::make_error_code(std::errc::timed_out));
// Error type here is std::error_code, NOT exception_ptr.
```

The handler in `upon_error` (or `let_error`) must accept **exactly this type** — passing a lambda with the wrong signature is a compile error.

---

## `upon_error` — converting an error into a value

`upon_error` was introduced in lesson 3. Briefly:

```cpp
upon_error(sender, fn)  // fn(ErrorType) -> Value
```

`fn` receives the **specific error type** of the sender and returns a **value** — the pipeline then continues on the `set_value` path. The key constraint: `fn` returns a **value**, not a sender.

```cpp
auto pipeline =
    risky_sender
    | std::execution::upon_error([](std::error_code ec) {
        // ec is already the right type — no dynamic_cast needed
        return ec == std::errc::timed_out ? 0 : -1;
    });
```

---

## `let_error` — the error opens a new pipeline

`let_error` is the powerful sibling of `upon_error`: instead of a value, the function returns a **new sender**.

```cpp
let_error(sender, fn)  // fn(ErrorType) -> Sender
```

This lets you launch a full operation on the error path — for example, contact a backup data source, retry, or write diagnostics:

```cpp
auto pipeline =
    primary_source()
    | std::execution::let_error([](std::error_code ec) {
        // Return a new sender, not a value:
        return fallback_source();
    });
```

The analogy with the value path: `then` returns a value, `let_value` returns a new sender. Likewise, `upon_error` returns a value, `let_error` returns a new sender.

| Adaptor | Path | fn returns |
|---|---|---|
| `then` | value | value |
| `let_value` | value | new sender |
| `upon_error` | error | value |
| `let_error` | error | new sender |

---

## Stop tokens in `std::execution`

Every **receiver** connected to a sender has a `get_stop_token()` method. The sender can query it and check whether cancellation has been requested:

```cpp
// Inside a custom sender implementation:
auto token = std::execution::get_stop_token(receiver);
if (token.stop_requested()) {
    // Finish cleanly via the stopped channel:
    std::execution::set_stopped(std::move(receiver));
    return;
}
```

Cancellation propagates **top-down**: when a parent requests a stop, the `stop_token` of the child receiver starts returning `true`. This is exactly how `when_all` cancels remaining senders when one of them errors (see lesson 4).

---

## `stop_when(s, stop_token)` — linking external cancellation to a pipeline

```cpp
auto cancelable = std::execution::stop_when(my_pipeline, external_token);
```

`stop_when` wraps sender `s` so that if `external_token` fires, `s` also receives `stop_requested`. Use this when you need to tie a pipeline to an external cancellation source — a Cancel button or a timeout:

```cpp
std::stop_source user_cancel;

// Trigger cancellation from another thread:
// user_cancel.request_stop();

auto pipeline = std::execution::stop_when(
    long_operation(),
    user_cancel.get_token()
);
```

---

## Why three channels beat exception-only

| Property | `std::future` | `std::execution` senders |
|---|---|---|
| Error type | Always `exception_ptr` | Any type — part of the sender's type |
| Cancellation | No (or exception-as-workaround) | Separate `set_stopped` channel |
| Zero overhead when unused | No | Yes — unused channels compile away |
| Typed error handling | No — `dynamic_cast` inside `catch` | Yes — lambda with the right type |

---

## Pattern: converting error representations

Sometimes the lower layer returns `std::error_code` but the upper layer expects `std::exception_ptr`. The conversion is straightforward:

```cpp
auto pipeline =
    io_operation()
    | std::execution::upon_error([](std::error_code ec) -> int {
        throw std::system_error{ec};  // convert error_code to an exception
        return 0;  // never reached, but needed for the return type
    });
```

Or via `let_error`:

```cpp
auto pipeline =
    io_operation()
    | std::execution::let_error([](std::error_code ec) {
        return std::execution::just_error(
            std::make_exception_ptr(std::system_error{ec})
        );
    });
```

